package arch.day38;

import java.util.*;

/**
 * Day 38 Assignment: Circular Dependency Detection and Refactoring.
 * Simulates how Spring detects cyclic bean dependencies at startup
 * using depth-first search, then demonstrates the refactoring fix.
 */
public class Day38Exercise {

    record BeanDep(String name, List<String> deps) {}

    static List<String> detectCycle(Map<String, BeanDep> graph) {
        Set<String> visited = new HashSet<>();
        Set<String> onStack = new HashSet<>();
        List<String> path = new ArrayList<>();
        for (String bean : graph.keySet()) {
            if (!visited.contains(bean)) {
                if (dfs(bean, graph, visited, onStack, path)) {
                    return new ArrayList<>(path);
                }
            }
        }
        return Collections.emptyList();
    }

    static boolean dfs(String bean, Map<String, BeanDep> graph,
                       Set<String> visited, Set<String> onStack, List<String> path) {
        visited.add(bean);
        onStack.add(bean);
        path.add(bean);
        BeanDep node = graph.get(bean);
        if (node != null) {
            for (String dep : node.deps()) {
                if (!visited.contains(dep)) {
                    if (dfs(dep, graph, visited, onStack, path)) return true;
                } else if (onStack.contains(dep)) {
                    path.add(dep);
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }
        onStack.remove(bean);
        path.remove(path.size() - 1);
        return false;
    }

    static void analyse(String label, Map<String, BeanDep> graph) {
        System.out.println(label);
        graph.forEach((k, v) -> System.out.println("  " + k + " -> " + v.deps()));
        List<String> cycle = detectCycle(graph);
        if (cycle.isEmpty()) {
            System.out.println("  Result: NO CYCLE - context will start successfully.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("  Result: CYCLE DETECTED - " + String.join(" -> ", cycle));
            System.out.println("  Spring: 'The dependencies of some beans form a cycle'");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: Original graph with cycle
        Map<String, BeanDep> before = new LinkedHashMap<>();
        before.put("NotificationService", new BeanDep("NotificationService", List.of("UserService")));
        before.put("UserService",         new BeanDep("UserService",         List.of("AuditService")));
        before.put("AuditService",        new BeanDep("AuditService",        List.of("NotificationService")));
        analyse("--- Before refactoring ---", before);

        // Step 2: Refactored graph - extract shared AuditLogger bean
        Map<String, BeanDep> after = new LinkedHashMap<>();
        after.put("NotificationService", new BeanDep("NotificationService", List.of("AuditLogger")));
        after.put("UserService",         new BeanDep("UserService",         List.of("AuditLogger")));
        after.put("AuditService",        new BeanDep("AuditService",        List.of("AuditLogger")));
        after.put("AuditLogger",         new BeanDep("AuditLogger",         Collections.emptyList()));
        analyse("--- After refactoring (AuditLogger extracted) ---", after);

        // Step 3: Refactoring summary
        System.out.println("--- Refactoring principle ---");
        System.out.println("  Original cycle: NotificationService -> UserService -> AuditService -> NotificationService");
        System.out.println("  Root cause: AuditService needed NotificationService to send audit alerts.");
        System.out.println("  Fix: extract the shared logging concern into AuditLogger (leaf bean, no deps).");
        System.out.println("  All three services depend on AuditLogger. No service depends on another.");
        System.out.println("  Spring can now instantiate: AuditLogger first, then the three services.");
    }
}

conceptual.answer:
`@Configuration` marks a class as a source of `@Bean` method definitions. Spring processes it specially: the class is subclassed by **CGLIB** at runtime before any beans are created.

Here is why: without CGLIB, calling one `@Bean` method from another inside the same `@Configuration` class would create a new object every time. Consider:
```java
@Bean public DataSource dataSource() { return new HikariDataSource(config); }
@Bean public JdbcTemplate jdbc() { return new JdbcTemplate(dataSource()); }
@Bean public TransactionManager tx() { return new DataSourceTransactionManager(dataSource()); }
```
Without CGLIB, `dataSource()` would be called twice and you would have two `DataSource` instances — a connection pool leak. With CGLIB, the proxy intercepts the `dataSource()` call from inside `jdbc()` and `tx()` and returns the existing singleton instance instead of calling the real method again.

This is why `@Configuration` classes cannot be `final` and `@Bean` methods cannot be `final` — CGLIB cannot subclass or override `final` members. A class annotated with `@Configuration(proxyBeanMethods = false)` skips CGLIB but then `@Bean` methods called internally are not intercepted and each call creates a new instance.

followUps.answer:
Annotate each implementation class (or `@Bean` method) with `@Profile("prod")` or `@Profile("dev")`:
```java
@Service @Profile("prod") public class StripePaymentProcessor implements PaymentProcessor {}
@Service @Profile("dev")  public class FakePaymentProcessor implements PaymentProcessor {}
```
Spring registers only the bean matching the active profile. Your `OrderService` constructor declares `PaymentProcessor` — it receives whichever implementation is active. This is clean because the selection is configuration-driven, not `if-else` in code. For tests, use `@ActiveProfiles("dev")` to activate the fake implementation without any code change.

