Yes. Define an annotation meta-annotated with `@Qualifier`:
```java
// @Target({FIELD, PARAMETER, METHOD})
// @Retention(RUNTIME)
// @Qualifier
// public @interface EmailChannel {}
```
Then annotate the bean: `@Component @EmailChannel public class EmailNotificationService ...` and the injection point: `@EmailChannel NotificationService email`. This is type-safe — renaming the annotation is a compile error caught by the IDE, whereas a typo in `@Qualifier("emailNotifiction")` is only caught at runtime when the context fails to start. Custom qualifiers also support attributes: `@Channel(type = "email")` can carry metadata.

